00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:54.199
But I'm going to use the IMDB site here as a convenient example of how to scrape web

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:55.199
data.

00:03:55.199 --> 00:04:02.839
And the way we're going to do this is with a strategy that relies on the nature of webpages.

00:04:02.839 --> 00:04:09.759
So just to quickly review how webpages work, every website that you visit is stored as

00:04:09.759 --> 00:04:13.100
a set of instructions on a web server somewhere.

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:16.679
You visit it through a web browser on your computer, and the first thing that happens

00:04:16.679 --> 00:04:20.700
when you try to access that website is your computer sends a request to the server that

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:22.059
hosts the website.

00:04:22.059 --> 00:04:28.140
When the server gets that request, normally, it sends back an HTML document that contains

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:32.260
all the instructions that your web browser needs to build the webpage you're trying to

00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:33.940
visit.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:37.859
Once your web browser has that document, then it uses those instructions to put together

00:04:37.859 --> 00:04:40.779
the webpage, and you see it there on your computer.

00:04:40.779 --> 00:04:44.940
And from that point, various exchanges can happen and things occur, but this is the basics

00:04:44.940 --> 00:04:47.459
of every webpage.

00:04:47.459 --> 00:04:52.220
If you were to look at the HTML document that your web browser receives, it's just text.

00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:53.220
Text instructions.

00:04:53.220 --> 00:04:57.500
It's formatted a particular way, but everything that appears on that webpage will be mentioned

00:04:57.500 --> 00:05:03.579
somewhere here in the instructions, and this is the kernel of our strategy for web scraping.

00:05:03.579 --> 00:05:15.700
If we were to go to IMDb, here's the webpage in real life.

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:20.700
Let's say we wanted to look at the cast of this movie, so IMDb displays the cast very

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:22.100
prominently in this table here.

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:26.579
We can see the star was Kristen Bell, and then Idina Menzel, and so on.

00:05:26.579 --> 00:05:30.140
If we wanted to get that information, we could certainly come here and look at it and write

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:32.940
it down ourselves, but that's not efficient at all.

00:05:33.299 --> 00:05:37.380
Instead, we could look at the HTML source for the webpage.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:40.100
Now, Chrome makes it very easy to look at the source for a webpage.

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:44.059
You don't need to do this to scrape data, but I just want to show you what it looks like.

00:05:44.059 --> 00:05:45.579
Here's the source for that webpage.

00:05:45.579 --> 00:05:51.420
It's quite complicated, but if we were trying to find Kristen Bell, we should be able to

00:05:51.420 --> 00:05:55.859
use our search feature, and we see that every mention of her in the webpage is also somewhere

00:05:55.859 --> 00:05:58.980
here in this text.

00:05:58.980 --> 00:06:05.059
We just have to find it and extract it.

00:06:05.059 --> 00:06:08.899
If we wanted to find Kristen Bell in this webpage, or any actor in the webpage, we just

00:06:08.899 --> 00:06:13.260
need to find the source and extract it from the correct location in the source.

00:06:13.260 --> 00:06:15.500
That's going to be our basic strategy for web scraping.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:19.420
We're pulling things out of the source of the webpage.

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:22.899
You could look at that source, and it probably occurred to you that that's just one giant

00:06:22.899 --> 00:06:26.619
character string, and you could use regular expressions and character string manipulations

00:06:26.820 --> 00:06:31.980
to extract pieces of that, and perhaps you'd feel comfortable doing that, but that's not

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:35.940
a very efficient way to go about extracting information from an HTML document, because

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:38.220
HTML is meant to have a structure.

00:06:38.220 --> 00:06:42.420
It's based around a structure, and if you understand that structure, you can extract

00:06:42.420 --> 00:06:46.700
information from the document in a more precise and targeted way.

00:06:46.700 --> 00:06:50.299
If there are any beginners out there who are seeing HTML now and starting to get afraid,

00:06:50.299 --> 00:06:51.299
don't worry.

00:06:51.299 --> 00:06:54.579
By the end of this webinar, you'll see that you don't have to touch the HTML.

00:06:54.579 --> 00:06:57.899
We'll use our tools to do that, but it is important to have at least some idea of what

00:06:57.899 --> 00:07:03.019
context this web scraping activity is occurring in.

00:07:03.019 --> 00:07:05.500
Let's look at the structure of HTML very quickly.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:10.380
HTML organizes content by placing tags around the content.

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:12.179
Here's an example tag.

00:07:12.179 --> 00:07:17.140
This piece of HTML would create a link to github.com, and the link would appear in a

00:07:17.140 --> 00:07:19.380
document as just the word github.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:22.500
If you open this in a web browser, that word would probably be blue or something, so you

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:25.899
know that there's a link and you can click on it.

00:07:25.899 --> 00:07:29.179
The tag here in this piece of code is A. It stands for anchor.

00:07:29.179 --> 00:07:36.019
It's for web links, and the tag has a name, and it starts right after the less than sign.

00:07:36.019 --> 00:07:37.500
This tag also has an attribute.

00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:42.420
In this case, the attribute is named href, and the attribute has a value, and the value

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:46.779
is, in this case, the name of the website we want to link to, and then github itself

00:07:46.779 --> 00:07:48.179
is the content of the tag.

00:07:48.739 --> 00:07:53.579
When you're scraping data, you could scrape any of these things out of the HTML, but most

00:07:53.579 --> 00:07:59.540
often you'll want the actual content that's in your webpage or in the HTML.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:04.540
If we looked at that sample HTML that I put up on the screen a few moments ago, it's legitimate

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:05.540
HTML.

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:06.540
This is not the actual HTML for IMDB.

00:08:06.540 --> 00:08:11.299
We saw that was much more verbose and complex, but we can use this HTML to get a sense of

00:08:11.299 --> 00:08:13.739
how these tags are organized.

00:08:13.739 --> 00:08:17.220
Within any webpage, the tags are organized in a hierarchy.

00:08:17.820 --> 00:08:24.019
This webpage here begins with an HTML tag, and then the next level of the hierarchy is

00:08:24.019 --> 00:08:28.619
a head tag and a body tag, which sort of divides the webpage into two, so we can visualize

00:08:28.619 --> 00:08:30.339
this as a tree.

00:08:30.339 --> 00:08:34.659
Under the head tag, we have some other tags, title, links, scripts, and under the body

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:36.739
tag, we have some tags.

00:08:36.739 --> 00:08:41.659
Those tags also have their own sub-tags, for example, p and span here, and beneath p, we

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:48.260
have a b tag, and then we have some tables with their own items.

00:08:48.260 --> 00:08:52.059
Now if you wanted to find a piece of content in this simple webpage, for example, if you

00:08:52.059 --> 00:08:57.179
want to find the word here, all you would need to know is that it occurs inside the

00:08:57.179 --> 00:09:01.539
b tag, and the b tag's in this location, and then you can search for that b tag and extract

00:09:01.539 --> 00:09:04.099
this content, and you'd have the word here.

00:09:04.099 --> 00:09:10.619
This is sort of what we're going to do when we scrape data out of our webpages.

00:09:10.619 --> 00:09:14.739
If we want to find Kristen Bell's name, she's the lead actress here, we would need to figure

00:09:14.739 --> 00:09:19.700
out which HTML tag surrounds her name in the code.

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:23.020
In this case, since I have the source code up, I'll search for her name, and I found

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:24.020
it.

00:09:24.020 --> 00:09:29.460
Here, she's the star of the show, so her name's mentioned in several places, but I'm most

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:32.619
interested in this piece here, because if I can extract Kristen Bell in this table,

00:09:32.619 --> 00:09:36.500
then I should be able to extract every other actor or actress in the table, so we're looking

00:09:36.500 --> 00:09:37.500
at the cast table.

00:09:38.500 --> 00:09:42.260
I've already searched through this webpage a little bit, and you can see here's cast,

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:45.260
so this is the table, and here's Kristen Bell.

00:09:45.260 --> 00:09:48.059
This is referring to her picture, which appears in the table.

00:09:48.059 --> 00:09:54.260
Here's her actual name in the table, and we can see that it's contained in the span tag,

00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:59.940
so we know which tag surrounds Kristen Bell, but in this particular webpage, there are

00:09:59.940 --> 00:10:03.059
many, many span tags that are not just used for Kristen Bell's name.

00:10:03.059 --> 00:10:07.580
In fact, if we were to search the webpage, we'd see that there's about 600 span tags,

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:13.179
so we're off to a good start narrowing in on the content we want to get, but we're not

00:10:13.179 --> 00:10:14.340
narrow enough.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:17.900
We don't want to pull out 600 values and then have to search through those manually to get

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:22.179
Kristen Bell, and just as a reminder, the reason we're doing all this stuff, trying

00:10:22.179 --> 00:10:26.179
to find these tags and understand the structure and how our information's embedded in, because

00:10:26.179 --> 00:10:29.659
at the end of the day, we want to largely automate this process.

00:10:29.659 --> 00:10:31.500
We don't want to do things manually.

00:10:31.500 --> 00:10:36.460
We want to have our computer save us time by doing it for us.

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:40.619
Let's look at how we could zoom in or be a little more targeted when we search for Kristen

00:10:40.619 --> 00:10:41.619
Bell.

00:10:41.619 --> 00:10:46.940
We're going to use more than just the HTML tag to describe and locate her name in this

00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:51.700
document, and we're going to do that by taking advantage of another technology that's used

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:54.460
with webpages, and that's CSS.

00:10:54.460 --> 00:10:59.539
So if you're not familiar with CSS, here's a very brief introduction.

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:04.299
If you have an HTML document with those tags you're looking at, you'll be able to create

00:11:04.299 --> 00:11:08.580
a page that has text and links and paragraphs and stuff, but it's going to look very plain

00:11:08.580 --> 00:11:11.140
because HTML doesn't really contain all that much.

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:15.659
I think there's like 100 tags you can use, but they're all very basic.

00:11:15.659 --> 00:11:19.500
So if you consider a webpage you might have visited, like shiny.rstudio.com, if you look

00:11:19.500 --> 00:11:23.380
just at the HTML of the webpage, it would build something that looks like this, a plain

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:24.380
white document.

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:27.299
And if you've ever tried to load a webpage with a really slow connection, you might have

00:11:27.299 --> 00:11:29.580
actually seen a webpage that looked like this.

00:11:29.580 --> 00:11:33.299
Your computer was just trying to help you out and show you what it can before the rest

00:11:33.299 --> 00:11:35.619
of the information related to the webpage showed up.

00:11:35.619 --> 00:11:38.299
That information would be CSS.

00:11:38.299 --> 00:11:43.299
You combine CSS with an HTML document, you get a styled webpage.

00:11:43.299 --> 00:11:47.380
So this is how the shiny.rstudio.com webpage looks if you visit it, and you'll notice it

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:51.400
has the same components, it has the same text and the same web links and stuff, but they

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:52.400
all look different.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:56.219
They have a different style, and it's that style that really makes the visual experience

00:11:56.219 --> 00:11:59.500
that you want to have when you visit the webpage.

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:07.020
If we understand how CSS works, we can use it to scrape data as well as style webpages.

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:10.580
So if you look at an example CSS file, you'd see something that looks a little bit like

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:12.099
this.

00:12:12.099 --> 00:12:14.299
These are sets of instructions.

00:12:14.299 --> 00:12:17.700
Between the brackets here we have actual pieces of styling.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:24.080
So color colon FFFFF, that's choosing a specific color for something to be.

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:27.640
And then we're choosing a width lower down, and we're choosing a background color lower

00:12:27.640 --> 00:12:28.640
down.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:29.880
This is styling.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:34.840
The other part of the CSS, the part that we'll rely on, are selectors.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:39.880
So where it says spanner.num or table.data, this tells your web browser which parts of

00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:42.679
the HTML document to apply the styling to.

00:12:42.679 --> 00:12:48.440
For example, that color FFFFF, that's only going to be applied to span tags.

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:50.239
We've already seen some span tags.

00:12:50.239 --> 00:12:54.880
So any span tag in that hypothetical webpage will have a certain color.

00:12:54.880 --> 00:12:58.640
And then we'll see what .num describes and table.data describes.

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:05.119
But these selectors are a way to specify specific elements in the webpage to then apply styling

00:13:05.119 --> 00:13:06.119
to.

00:13:06.119 --> 00:13:09.640
But this idea of specifying a specific element in a webpage is how you're going to extract

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:11.719
specific elements as data.

00:13:11.719 --> 00:13:12.799
We use the same system.

00:13:12.799 --> 00:13:16.119
So let's look at the basics of this system.

00:13:16.119 --> 00:13:18.679
Here is an HTML tag.

00:13:18.679 --> 00:13:19.679
It's a span tag.

00:13:20.119 --> 00:13:22.119
Notice this tag has a class and an ID attribute.

00:13:22.119 --> 00:13:23.119
It has some content.

00:13:23.119 --> 00:13:25.119
Content here says shiny.

00:13:25.119 --> 00:13:28.320
Here's our class, here's our ID.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:30.559
You know it because that's the names.

00:13:30.559 --> 00:13:35.679
And then here's a selector that we can use in CSS to describe this tag.

00:13:35.679 --> 00:13:41.440
The word span in the selector will refer to every span tag that exists in your HTML document.

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:43.760
And since this is a span tag, it will refer to this as well.

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:47.760
So any styling we group under the span tag will be applied here.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:52.280
But we could also be more specific in the way we apply our styling.

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:54.919
We could apply our styling based on class.

00:13:54.919 --> 00:13:57.320
So this span tag has a class big name.

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:01.599
If we want to create a CSS selector that says find all the elements who have the class big

00:14:01.599 --> 00:14:06.440
name, we do that by putting a period and then big name.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:13.039
So that period prefix tells your web browser that this selector is a class selector.

00:14:13.039 --> 00:14:17.520
It matches everything that has the class big name.

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:21.719
And if we put that period together with span, now we're saying we want to match everything

00:14:21.719 --> 00:14:25.679
that is both a span element and a big name class.

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:28.039
So it's even more specific.

00:14:28.039 --> 00:14:30.760
And then we could also be very, very precise.

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:37.719
And if we set an ID name for a tag, then we can refer to that tag by its ID with a hashtag.

00:14:37.719 --> 00:14:40.359
So hashtag shiny would refer to anything that has the ID shiny.

00:14:40.359 --> 00:14:45.840
But normally when you write a webpage, only one thing will have that ID.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:48.599
So those selectors we saw there refer to different things.

00:14:48.599 --> 00:14:52.719
And the way they refer to them is with the prefix that is put in front of them.

00:14:52.719 --> 00:14:57.679
The prefixes that you could use are no prefix, which refers to the tag name, a dot, which

00:14:57.679 --> 00:15:02.599
refers to the class name, and a hashtag that refers to an ID.

00:15:02.599 --> 00:15:04.039
Now will there be a quiz on this later?

00:15:04.039 --> 00:15:05.039
Yeah, kind of.

00:15:05.039 --> 00:15:06.840
You don't actually need to remember all this.

00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:08.200
I'm going to show you a tool that does it for you.

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:11.640
But you will need to be familiar with this if you want to understand what's going on.

00:15:11.640 --> 00:15:12.640
All right.

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:16.080
So which CSS end identifiers are associated with Kristen Bell's name?

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:23.479
Well, if we go back over here, we see it's a span that has the class item prop, and item

