nodes and CSS selectors. You can use the Selector Gadget to get those selectors, but now I'm

00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:21.719
getting ahead of myself. Finally, once you have the nodes, you extract the content with

00:31:21.719 --> 00:31:28.119
the helper function, which is normally HTML text. If your node is a table, you can extract

00:31:28.119 --> 00:31:33.079
the whole table as a R-friendly data frame with HTML table, and then you can use the

00:31:33.079 --> 00:31:38.199
Selector Gadget widget to find useful selector combinations to get just the information that

00:31:38.199 --> 00:31:42.800
you want. This is the best way to go about it, because there's not necessarily going

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:47.319
to be much rhyme or reason, or intuition to follow about which CSS selectors best describe

00:31:47.319 --> 00:31:53.400
